Incident.Summary: The driver was arrested for DUI/DWI.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
*In-Car Camera, W-17 operable.
*Body-Worn Camera operable.

Defendant: Garrett Wayne Willis  

Date of Birth: 11/08/1995

Date of Arrest: 08/26/2023

Time of Arrest: 0210 hours

License#: F601881 / West Virginia Driver's License

DUI#: 23-070

CERTIFICATES AND TRAINING:

*I am trained to administer Standardized Field Sobriety Tests through the Maryland State Police and the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
*I am trained and certified to conducted preliminary breathalyzer tests by the Maryland State Police. 
*I have successfully completed the Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement Course in November 2020.
*I have successfully completed the Drug Recognition Expert Course and have been certified as a DRE (# 38230) by the International Association of Chiefs of Police as of June 2023.  

VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1)

     On 08/26/2023 at approximately 0157 hours, I was on duty, in uniform, operating MSP marked unit W-17. I was traveling southbound on Garrett Highway, north of Jeffrey Lane, Oakland, Garrett County, MD 21550. I observed a vehicle directly in front of me pulled over on the right shoulder of the southbound lane on Garrett Highway, north of Jeffrey Lane, Oakland, Garrett County, MD 21550. As I approached the vehicle, I observed the vehicle pull onto the southbound lane directly in front of me, travel approximately 50 feet, and pull back onto the right shoulder of the southbound lane of Garrett Highway. I observed the vehicle activate it's four way flashing lights. I pulled onto the shoulder of the southbound lane of Garrett Highway directly behind the vehicle, activated my rear facing emergency equipment and conducted a welfare check of the vehicle. The vehicle was a white Dodge Ram bearing West Virginia registration "O5D343."

PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2)

     Upon making contact with the driver, I detected the strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath and person. I observed his eyes were bloodshot and glassy, his speech was thick and slurred, and his body movements to be slow and lethargic. The driver appeared to be disoriented. I identified the driver as Garrett Wayne Willis (W/M DOB: 11/08/1995) by his MVA photograph through METERS. I asked Willis if he was ok. Willis stated, "Yeah I literally just pulled out in front of a cop. I pulled into the fast lane, so I could pass you all. And then you pulled out and....yeah and I pulled over." It should be noted there is no "fast lane" as there is only one southbound and northbound lane on Garrett Highway in that area. I asked Willis where he was coming from. Willis stated, "Big Bear." I asked how many alcoholic beverages he had consumed. Willis stated, "About 2 shots." I asked Willis to retrieve his driver's license. Willis advised he did not have his driver's license with him. I asked Willis what his date of birth was. Willis stated, "1998...November." I asked Willis what day his date of birth was. Willis stated, "November 8th." Willis stated, "We pulled out as soon as the cop pulled in behind us, we just pulled out." I asked Willis to attempt field sobriety tests which he agreed. I observed Willis grab the arm rest of the driver side door of the vehicle, with his left hand, to steady himself as he stepped out of the vehicle. While speaking with Willis away from the vehicle, I continued to smell a strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath and person. I observed Willis lean back against the hood of his vehicle to maintain his balance. 


PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)

     The evaluation was performed on the right shoulder, in front of Willis' vehicle. The surface was dry, relatively level, and free of any debris. Lighting conditions consisted of streetlights, my patrol vehicle's headlights, Willis' vehicle's headlights, and my flashlight. My patrol vehicle's forward emergency lights were deactivated during all three tests. Willis appeared to be in good physical condition.

I asked Willis the following questions:

Glasses or Contacts - Yes. Willis advised he wears contacts.

Medical Conditions - No.

Injuries - No. 

Medications - Yes. Willis advised he had taken Ibuprofen. 


     The first test given was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus test. The tip of my finger was used as the test’s stimulus and held approximately 12 inches from Willis’ eyes, slightly above eye level. Willis was instructed to look straight ahead, keeping his head still while following and focusing on the tip of the stimulus with his eyes, until told to stop. Willis was positioned in a manner to ensure the headlights of passing traffic would not interfere with the test results. I asked Willis if he was able to see the tip of the stimulus, and if he understood the test. Willis replied “Yes” to both questions.

 

Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus (6/6 clues observed)

  1. Lack of Smooth Pursuit - Present in both eyes.
  2. Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at maximum deviation - Present in both eyes.
  3. Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees - Present in both eyes.

Note* I did not observe Vertical Gaze Nystagmus.

Walk And Turn (7/8 clues observed)

     Prior to Willis performing the test, I explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. Willis was instructed to place his right foot directly in front of his left foot and touch heel to toe. Willis was instructed and demonstrated to place his hands flat at his sides and to remain in the position until told to begin. Willis was advised to take nine (9) steps in a straight line touching heel to toe on every step. Willis was to keep his hands flat at his sides, keep his eyes focused on his feet, and to count every step out loud. On the ninth step, Willis was explained and demonstrated to keep his lead foot on the line, and to take a series of small steps around with his rear foot to turn completely around. Willis was again explained and demonstrated the second series of nine (9) steps were to be performed identical to the first series of nine (9) steps. Willis was instructed that once he began the test that he was not to stop walking until the test was completed, keep his hands down by his sides, look down at his feet, and count each step out loud. Willis stated he understood the instructions and was able to complete the test.

Instructional Stage:   

  1. Willis was unable to maintain balance by stepping offline by more than one half inch on two (2) occasions. 

Walking Stage (1st Nine)

  1. Improper amount of steps. (10 steps).

Walking Stage (2nd Nine)

  1. Stepped offline by more than one half inch. (Step 1).
  2. Missed heel to toe by more than one half inch. (Step 4). 
  3. Raised arms away from torso by more than 6 inches. (During the turn).
  4. Improper amount of steps. (11 steps).
  5. Stopped the test. (Willis stopped the test after he turned, before continuing the test). 

Turn: Unsatisfactory. (Willis did not plant his lead foot. Willis took an adjustment step backwards with his lead foot. Willis raised his arms away from his torso by more than six (6) inches. Willis raised his right foot to the side approximately two (2) feet in order to maintain balance. Willis placed his right foot down next to his left foot and stopped the test to regain balance, before continuing the test).

One Leg Stand (4/4 Clues observed)

     Prior to Willis performing the test, I explained and demonstrated how the test should be conducted. Willis was instructed to stand with his heels together and hands down by his sides while the instructions were given and during the test. When instructed to start, he was to raise the foot of his choice off the ground approximately 6 inches. While his leg was raised he was to keep his leg straight, watch his raised foot, and to count out loud by thousands (one thousand-one, one thousand-two) and to continue the test until told to stop. Willis stated he understood the instructions and was able to complete the test.


Seconds 1-10:

  1. Raised arms away from torso by more than 6 inches (Seconds 3-8).
  2. Sways (Seconds 4 and 6).
  3. Hops (Seconds 4-7).
  4. Puts foot down (Seconds 3 and 8). 

Seconds 11-20:
  1. Sways (Seconds 16 and 19).
  2. Puts foot down (Second 12). 
Note * Willis put his foot down on second 12 and did not raise his foot again until second 19.

Seconds 21-30:
  1. Puts foot down (Second 27). 
Note* Willis put his foot down on second 27 and did not raise his foot again.
Note* Willis was offered the preliminary breath test, which he voluntarily agreed to take, which resulted in a (BrAC) of .24

ARREST

     Based on the following, I believed Willis was driving a motor vehicle under the influence of alcohol:

*Strong odor of an alcoholic beverage emitting from his breath.

*My observed signs of impairment as he performed field sobriety tests.

*Glassy and bloodshot eyes, thick and slurred speech.

*Slow and lethargic body movements.

*Disoriented.

*Willis's admission to consuming alcoholic beverages.

     Willis was arrested for driving under the influence of alcohol at approximately 0210 hours and was placed in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle. Willis was transported to the Maryland State Police McHenry Barrack for processing. Willis's mouth was checked at approximately 0210 hours. While at the barrack, Willis was read the DR-15 Advice of Rights at approximately 0243 hours, at the conclusion of reading the DR-15, Willis advised he did not wish to take a test of breath and instead insisted on taking a blood test. I informed Willis that would require a trip to the hospital. Willis continued to insist he wished to take a blood test. 
     At approximately 0255 hours, I placed Willis in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle and transported him to Garrett Regional Medical Center located at 251 N. 4th Street, Oakland, Garrett County, MD to complete a blood test (Blood Kit # W-114). The blood draw was performed by Daniel Bailer RN at approximately 0317 hours. 

     Willis was given all copies of pertinent paperwork and was released to a sober driver at the hospital at approximately 0335 hours. 

     Case remains open pending the results of the blood test.

     All events occurred in Garrett County, Maryland.

On 11/27/2023 at approximately 1057 hours, I received the blood results, via email, from the Maryland State Police Forensic Sciences Division. The results revealed Willis had a Br(AC) of .20. 

     Case remains open pending issuance of a criminal summons, charging Willis with:
  • (TA 21-902 (a1i) Driving under the influence of alcohol.
  • (TA 21-902 (a1ii) Driving under the influence of alcohol per se. 
  • (TA 21-902 (b1i) Driving while impaired. 
  • (TA 21-902 (c1i) Driving so far impaired by alcohol, can not drive safely. 
  • (TA 21-901.1 (a) Reckless Driving. 
  • (TA 21-901.1 (b) Negligent Driving. 
     All events occurred in Garrett County, Maryland.

On 12/10/2023 at approximately 1350 hours, I made contact with Willis on the shoulder of Gorman Road and Steyer Gorman Road, Oakland, Garrett County, MD 21550. I advised Willis on the criminal summons and the lab results from his blood test. Willis signed all pertinent paperwork without incident. Willis made no statements regarding the incident. 

     Case closed by arrest.

     All events occurred in Garrett County, Maryland.

On 12/28/2023 at approximately 1412 hours, I received an email from the Maryland State Police McHenry Barrack duty officer, advising he received a phone call from a Sgt Lambert with the Grant County WV Sheriff's Office. The duty officer advised Sgt Lambert informed him Willis may have lied to me about his true identity. 

     I made contact with Sgt Lambert via phone. Sgt Lambert advised Garrett Willis is a school teacher and has no criminal record. Sgt Lambert advised Garrett has a younger brother, who looks alot like him, named Nathan Ryan Willis (W/M DOB: 03/03/1999). Sgt Lambert advised Nathan has been charged with at least four (4) DUIs in West Virginia, and currently has a revoked driver's license. Sgt Lambert advised this is not the first time Nathan has identified himself as his brother, Garrett. Sgt Lambert advised Nathan had been arrested recently in Keyser, WV for a DUI and when the arresting officer asked him for his identity, Nathan informed the officer his name was Garrett Willis. I confirmed through a METERS check that Nathan has a West Virginia Driver's license that is currently revoked.

     On 01/05/2024 at approximately 0625 hours, I emailed Sgt Lambert four (4) digital photographs I obtained from my body camera footage of Nathan on the night of the incident. Sgt Lambert was able to positively identify the suspect as Nathan Willis. I made contact with the Garrett County State's Attorney Christian Mash and advised him on the incident.

     Case remains open pending issuance of an arrest warrant, charging Nathan with:
  • 1 0690 (CR 9-502) False Statement to a Peace Officer upon arrest.
  • 1 0207 (CR 9-501) False Statement to a Peace Officer.
  • 1 6356 (TA 21-902 (a1) Driving under the influence of alcohol.
  • 1 6357 (TA 21-902 (a2) Driving under the influence of alcohol per se. 
  • 1 4583 (TA 21-902 (b1) Driving while impaired.
  • 1 4585 (TA 21-902 (c1) Driving while so far impaired.
  • 3100 (TA 16-303 (g) Driving with an out of state revoked driver's license.
  • 1 5664 (TA 21-901.1 (a) Reckless driving.
  • 2 1334 (TA 21-901.1 (b) Negligent driving.
  • 1 6824 (TA 16-112 (c) Fail to display license upon demand.
     All events occurred in Garrett County, Maryland.

On 01/07/2024 at approximately 1230 hours an extraditable arrest warrant was issued on Nathan. I made contact with Sgt Lambert of the Grant County, WV Sheriff's Office and advised him on the warrant.

     On 01/12/2024 at approximately 1122 hours, I made contact with Sgt Lambert, via phone. Sgt Lambert advised he had arrested Nathan and charged him with violation of parole. Sgt Lambert advised Nathan is currently being held at the Potomac Highlands Regional Jail located at 355 Dolan Drive, Augusta, WV 26704. Sgt Lambert advised Nathan had a waiver hearing before a judge for the extradition. Sgt Lambert advised the judge ruled Nathan to remain in the custody of the Potomac Highlands Regional Jail. Sgt Lambert advised Nathan would be serving a sentence for local charges with a maximum sentence of seventeen (17) months. Sgt Lambert advised once Nathan has served his sentence, he would be released for an extradition into my custody. 

     A copy of the arrest warrant was sent to the Potomac Highlands Regional Jail as a detainer. 

     On 01/12/2024 at approximately 1700 hours, I made contact with Garrett Willis via phone and advised him on the incident. 

     Case has been placed in active warrant status.

     All events occurred in Garrett County, Maryland and West Virginia.
